    <section id="gap" class="scroll-mt-24 mt-12 sm:mt-16">
      <span class={`${pillClass("gap")} inline-flex`}>üîç The Gap</span>
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold mt-6 mb-5">What Urban Company Doesn't Handle</h2>
       <BrutalCard color="#ffffff" class="mt-6 p-6 sm:p-7 border-2 border-black shadow-[8px_8px_0_0_#000] rounded-2xl">
        <p class="text-base sm:text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-900 mb-4">
          Urban Company has excellent worker verification, OTP checks, and a booking lifecycle for a single user. However, for the remote owner, critical gaps remain:
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-4 text-base sm:text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-900">
            <li>**Role-based access and shared ownership:** The app assumes the booker is the primary user. There's no concept of a "co-owner," "tenant," or "on-site contact" with different permissions.</li>
            <li>**Unified communication & timeline:** Communication is fragmented across WhatsApp, SMS, and the UC app chat. There is no single, shared timeline visible to all stakeholders.</li>
            <li>**Remote-owner transparency during execution:** Monitoring tools like photos/checklists are primarily for internal compliance, not for providing a remote owner with a "before/after job report" or a workflow to "approve extra work."</li>
            <li>**Property-centric service history:** History is tied to a user account, not the property. A remote owner managing multiple properties lacks an aggregated view of a home's service history.</li>
        </ul>
        <BrutalCard color="#fef9c3" class="mt-6 p-5 border-2 border-black shadow-[6px_6px_0_0_#000] rounded-2xl">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-extrabold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-gray-900">Why This Matters</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base sm:text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-900">
            This friction creates an opportunity to unlock a premium segment of NRIs who will pay for "remote orchestration," not just on-demand service. It's a strategic gap to build a defensible moat.
          </p>
        </BrutalCard>
      </BrutalCard>
    </section>

    <section id="pain-points" class="scroll-mt-24 mt-12 sm:mt-16">
      <span class={`${pillClass("problem")} inline-flex`}>ü§ï Prioritized Pain Points</span>
      <BrutalCard color="#ffffff" class="mt-6 p-6 sm:p-7 border-2 border-black shadow-[8px_8px_0_0_#000] rounded-2xl">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold mb-4">Top 3 Pains for the NRI</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <article class="border-2 border-black rounded-2xl bg-white shadow-[6px_6px_0_0_#000] p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">1. Lack of explicit role-based multi-actor workflow</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm sm:text-base text-gray-800 leading-relaxed">The system assumes a single user, but reality involves an owner, an on-site contact, and sometimes a tenant. Roles like payer, scheduler, and reviewer are not modeled.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="border-2 border-black rounded-2xl bg-white shadow-[6px_6px_0_0_#000] p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">2. Fragmented communication & missing shared timeline</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm sm:text-base text-gray-800 leading-relaxed">Context lives in WhatsApp, booking in UC, and partner calls via SMS. The owner can‚Äôt reconstruct "what actually happened" without manual effort.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="border-2 border-black rounded-2xl bg-white shadow-[6px_6px_0_0_#000] p-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">3. Transparency gap for remote owner during execution</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm sm:text-base text-gray-800 leading-relaxed">There's no structured "live" view. Crucial decisions ("Should we replace this part for ‚Çπ3,500?") are made via ad-hoc calls with the least-informed person.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </BrutalCard>
    </section>

